<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Dishwasher not cleaning dishes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three categories of "not cleaning." Most LA calls trace to the first one.</h2>

    <p>"Dishes coming out dirty" is one of the most common dishwasher service calls we run, and the underlying causes split into three categories. Mechanical faults (spray arm, wash pump, detergent dispenser, heating element). Water-side faults (inlet valve restriction, hard water mineral residue, water temperature too low). Loading and detergent problems (pre-rinsing too aggressively, wrong detergent, improper rack placement).</p>

    <p>Across SoCal, hard water is the silent variable that connects all three categories. LADWP, MWD, Calleguas, Santa Margarita, and Rancho California municipal water averages 12 to 18 grains per gallon. That mineral content accumulates in spray arm port holes, on the heating element, on the inlet valve screen, and in the detergent dispenser solenoid. A dishwasher that worked fine in year 3 starts producing dirty dishes in year 6 because mineral buildup has degraded multiple components simultaneously, even though the machine itself is functioning correctly.</p>

    <p>We service cleaning failures across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. <strong>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> Same-day across the central counties. BHGS Licensed #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). 90-day warranty.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TOP 6 CAUSES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Top 6 causes of poor cleaning</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">In honest frequency order.</h2>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>1. Clogged spray arm ports (30% of calls)</h3>
      <p>Calcium and magnesium from SoCal hard water deposit on the inside walls of spray arm port holes. Over years, the deposits narrow the openings, water pressure drops, and wash performance falls off. Dishes come out with food residue, streaks, and partial cleaning especially on the upper rack.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Pull the spray arms, hold up to light, look at the ports. Mineral buildup is unambiguous.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Vinegar soak (30 to 60 minutes), wire-brush the ports, reinstall. Often $89 diagnostic only, no parts. Spray arm replacement $180 to $340 if buildup is too severe to clear.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>2. Detergent dispenser not opening at the right time (15 to 20% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The dispenser door has a small wax motor or solenoid that releases at the correct point in the cycle. When that fails, the detergent stays trapped, and the wash phase runs without detergent. Dishes come out as if the cycle didn't run properly, because chemically it didn't.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Run a cycle, listen and watch through the door window if visible. If detergent is still in the dispenser at end of cycle, the dispenser failed.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Detergent dispenser assembly $200 to $380.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>3. Failing wash pump or circulation pump (15% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The wash pump (separate from the drain pump on most dishwashers) generates the water pressure that drives the spray arms. When the pump motor wears out, pressure drops, spray pattern weakens, dishes don't get hit hard enough to clean. Year 8 to 12 typical service life.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Listen during wash phase, measure pressure indirectly via spray arm rotation speed (slow rotation equals low pressure), amperage check on the motor.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Wash pump replacement $480 to $820 depending on brand and access difficulty.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>4. Water inlet valve mineral clog (10% of calls)</h3>
      <p>The inlet valve is the solenoid-controlled valve where water enters the dishwasher. The screen on the inlet side accumulates mineral buildup, reducing fill volume. Less water means lower wash pressure and incomplete cleaning. Often pairs with hard water symptoms elsewhere.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Time the fill cycle, measure water volume reaching the tub vs spec.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Inlet valve replacement $200 to $340.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>5. Heating element failure (10% of calls)</h3>
      <p>Wash water needs to be hot (130 to 140°F) for detergent to work and grease to release. If the heating element fails, water never heats during the wash cycle, grease persists on dishes, sometimes redepositing as a film. Less common on Bosch and Miele (which rely on water from the home water heater) than on KitchenAid, Whirlpool, GE which have in-tub heating.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Check water temperature mid-cycle with an instant-read thermometer or via control board diagnostic mode.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Heating element $260 to $460.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>6. Loading and detergent issues (10 to 15% of calls)</h3>
      <p>Honest framing: not every "not cleaning" call is a broken machine. Common patterns we find: customer pre-rinses dishes thoroughly (turbidity sensor reads load as clean, runs short cycle, dishes come out worse), uses pods in hard water without rinse aid, loads dishes facing the wrong direction, or runs Eco cycles expecting Heavy results. We tell you straight when the machine is fine and the cause is procedural.</p>
      <p><strong>Diagnostic:</strong> Visual loading check, detergent inspection, cycle setting confirmation.</p>
      <p><strong>Repair:</strong> $89 diagnostic only, plus advice. We don't manufacture repairs when the machine is working.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 HARD WATER DEEP DIVE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · SoCal hard water and your dishwasher</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cloudy glasses are not always the dishwasher's fault.</h2>

    <p>Across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside, municipal water hardness averages 12 to 18 grains per gallon. That puts SoCal in the upper third of US hardness. Glassware that comes out cloudy with white film is almost always hard water mineral residue, not a malfunction. The mineral content is also why every cleaning-related dishwasher repair we run includes a spray arm port inspection and an inlet valve screen check, both common buildup points.</p>

    <p>The practical maintenance protocol for SoCal:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Rinse aid in the dispenser, refilled monthly.</strong> Reduces spotting, helps drying, and improves cycle effectiveness in hard water meaningfully.</li>
      <li><strong>Citric-acid dishwasher cleaner monthly.</strong> Lemi Shine, Affresh, or generic equivalent. One cycle on Heavy with the cleaner clears mineral buildup before it accumulates.</li>
      <li><strong>Powder detergent over pods or gels in heavy-use households.</strong> Powders with water conditioners (Cascade Platinum Plus, Finish Quantum) outperform pods in hard water.</li>
      <li><strong>Whole-house water softener consideration if hardness exceeds 15 grains per gallon.</strong> Long-term solution that benefits the dishwasher, the washing machine, the water heater, and the whole house. Plumber trade for installation.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>None of these are sales pitches. We're an appliance repair company; we don't sell detergent, rinse aid, or water softeners. The recommendations are observational from running hundreds of service calls per year across SoCal.</p>
  </div>
</section>

